stylometry: Simulation models are used to solve "What-if" scenarios and they are beneficial because a company can use the model to solve several different problems quickly because they can easily change input and output cells and variables. They can also use them to determine what will make their business more efficient, for example, a supermarket can use a queuing model to determine how many cash registers they should have in order to shorten long lines and increase the amount of customers checking out in a given time. By using the model, they can figure out if purchasing more cash registers and hiring more cashiers will have any positive effect on their efficiency or if there will be too many empty check-out lines. Simulation models are an advantage because companies can determine if the changes they make to a situation will benefit them before they actually go and spend money on extra supplies, machinery, or employees.
